SUBSECTION.TEXT:
We say that $R(n)$ has order of growth 0e$\theta(f(n))$ (theta of $f(n)$) theta$\theta(f(n))$ (theta of $f(n)$) order notation $\Theta(f(n))$, written $R(n)=\Theta(f(n))$ (pronounced theta of $f(n)$), if there are positive constants $k_1$ and $k_2$ independent of $n$ such that
\[ \begin{array}{lllll} k_1\,f(n) & \leq & R(n) & \leq & k_2\,f(n) \end{array} \]
for any sufficiently large value of $n$. (In other words, for large $n$, the value $R(n)$ is sandwiched between $k_1f(n)$ and $k_2f(n)$.)
